text:
i met someone over twitter in 2015 who gave me my first piece of local press in portland. he followed me on my pdx journey and continued to follow me out of it. this person is the most talented and genuine writer i know - @indiealtpdx ...here we are, 4 years later and at last we made it into print. thank you brendan for always supporting me, @womencrushmusic and local music. thank you @vrtxmag for making this issue and giving us a platform to connect about this. it was so amazing to receive this in my mailbox today. 
shout out to all the other women who were featured in this issue and to the ones who weren't...we hear you. we see you. we love you.  #metoo #timesup

-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.

on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrestedÂ earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrestedÂ earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
what is going on with this world.. we are destroying ourselves from within... yes lets all  hide behind workouts and fine dining..what we wore 2day yesterday..and tomorrow....where we are going & where we left... but there comes  a time to stop and listen to what is happening in the real world...#metoo #blackvswhite #whitevsblack i grew up in the early 70's-80's grew older in the 90's & still in the 2000's... when i grew up i lived in #erie my 2 best ever friends where valerie and katrina... guess what they where african american yes black!!! 2  black girls going home for lunch at a white girls house singing to cyndi loper girls just wanna have fun in the school talent show... and noone thought any different... they where my rock!! i moved back home ðŸŒ where what do yu know its the 90's and r&b was the shit.... bell biv devoe..keith sweat...silk where the  bomb... coming back home i made new friends yes.. black friends who today...to this frigging day i consider them friends.. its not a world of 
black and white..white and black.. we need to be united.. not fighting against one another but with one another... #alllifesmatter #imamericanindian
unless we make it happen things will remain the same!!! #weareunitedarmy #unite #blackandwhite

we are gathered here today 
to get through this thing called life. 
electric word 
life it means forever & that's a mighty long time
but i'm here to tell you 
there's something else
the after world
a world of never ending happiness
you can always see the sun, day or night
so when u call up that shrink in beverly hill's, u know the one dr. everything'll be alright
instead of asking how much of your time is left ask him how much of your mind, baby
cause in this life things are much harder than the after world
..................................................
so if the elevator tries to bring u down go crazy, punch a higher floor lets go crazy lets get nuts" .................................. #princerogersnelson #letsgocrazy

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
ðŸ”ºanother virginia scandal
.
as the governor and attorney general of virginia face blackface scandals, the 3rd in line of succession (if gov. & ag resign) now faces disturbing allegations â€” lt. gov. justin fairfax (d) has been accused of sexual assault.
.
dr. vanessa c. tyson made the claim that in 2004, fairfax assaulted her, â€œwhat began as consensual kissing quickly turned into a sexual assaultâ€. fairfaxâ€™s lawyers deny the allegation as there is no corroborating evidence.
.
tysonâ€™s claim includes detailed of her assault, noting that fairfax held her head in his crotch then, â€œforced his penis into my mouth...as i cried and gagged, mr. fairfax forced me to perform oral sex on himâ€.
.
democrats agree that this is a credible allegation and must be investigated. note that the lawyers handling this matter for lt. gov. fairfax and dr. tyson are the same lawyers that represented now sc justice kavanaugh and his accuser, dr. christine blasey ford.
.
politics is at play here as well; if the gov. (d), ag (d), and lt. gov. (d) resign amidst their allegations and troubles, the very crucial swing-state of virginia would then be governed by a speaker of the house, kirk cox, a republican.
.
currently, there are no plans to resign among any of these men.
.
ðŸ”ºupdate feb 8: a second accuser has now gone public with allegations of being raped by fairfax in 2000. .

text:
"i wish able-bodied people knew disability care webs existed, that we nurture each other. maybe that would change some of their ideas that disability is a fate worse than death." leah lakshmi piepzna-samarasinha, @leahlakshmiwrites at explore more summit 2019
.
what if healing didn't have to mean fixed or cured, but instead focused on joy, pleasure, and access? too often able-bodied folks see disability as tragic, something to overcome, or something to be avoided at all costs.
.
yet, disabled people have always existed, will always exist, and have found creative, genius ways of surviving and adapting. disabled folks not only have an intimate understanding of what care means but they have had to find ways to exist in spaces that actively deny them access.
.
leah's new book, "care work" is a love letter to disabled, neurodivergent, and chronically ill folks. it's a testament to the incredible knowledge and wisdom that flourishes inside of disabled care that so many able-bodied folks don't even know exists.
.
what if the world was designed by disabled folks for disabled folks? all of us - all of us - would have access, care, and the resources we deserve to not only survive but to thrive. we won't be free until all of us are free, and that includes confronting our ableism and trusting the wisdom of disabled folks to help steer the ship.
.
you will not want to miss my chat with leah at explore more summit 2019. it's not only free to attend and entirely online, but all talks are captioned, too! grab your spot by registering at exploremoresummit.com today.
.
you deserve pleasure no matter what kind of body and ability you do or don't have. .

text:
when i was 16 i found myself in a dark alley with a boy in a parked car yelling, â€œno! stop!â€ i thought that night was ruining the rest of my life. i got home & couldnâ€™t cope with the shame, guilt, trauma so i turned to food. it filled my stomach and numbed the pain and put me into a carb coma of sleep.
.
over the next 7 years i got married to the best man and had 2 sons and could not figure out why i was still not just gaining weight but eating my feelings when i couldnâ€™t cope.
.
itâ€™d be a rough morning with the kids so during naptime iâ€™d eat a bag of ramen. then another. then a bowl of cereal. then another. pop tarts. chips. 2 dr. peppers...
.
see that night when i was 16 two things happened:
1) i was sexually assaulted
2) i developed binge eating disorder & food became my numbing drug of choice
.
until i figured that out i couldnâ€™t change. diets would lead to binges. once in the middle i even lost 100lbs and then between 2 more babies and a hard personal season gained 87lbs back. what iâ€™ve learned this last year and the â€œsecretâ€ to my weightloss is simply this...
.
the work is in your mind. diet and exerciseâ€” any of that could and should workâ€” but unless your mind is willing to do some hard processing and your soul some healing work you wonâ€™t make it.
.
an alcoholic admits they need help and seeks community and rids their atmosphere of the temptation & commits to a journey and a process before they start.
.
how is food addiction different?
.
get honest. do the steps. find support. determine to not relapse & stick with the diet you chose. day by day youâ€™ll get stronger.
.
xo,
115lbs down but moreso 338 days binge free.
.
.
.

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
commence panty bunching: these women were so ridiculous...not wanting to offer any approvals to the president's speech. i mean, i get it, he can be an ass as a person, but respect is due to the office. i was happy to see a few women buck their "societal expectations" and offer some clapping on positive changes that weren't just women's rights related.

and before you start saying shit. i believe in women's rights. i believe we are as good as the male sex. some things, we are better at. some, they certainly are better at. women can do and have the right to do the same things a man is allowed to do. but i also believe things shouldn't just be handed to us... because they aren't simply handed to men either. fair is fair. i've busted my ass to get where i am in my career.  and i have never experienced what so many of you females whine about were you say us women don't have equal rights (in the year 2000+). i've always demanded fairness and always gotten it. maybe rethink your approach because there must be a disparity in how you approach life... no one is going to hand you a good life. shut up and work for it.

as far as the #metoo thing? yep, i've been disrespected by a few men in my life. even had my mother defend one of those men, saying i claimed rape (no, he as her boyfriend, grabbed my ass in her house, clearly not rape). i've had a man shove his hand down my pants when i was 15. i've had two men think they had their "rights" to me when i was drunk. but those experiences are not who i am and i never allowed them to go further than what i've described here. i stopped every one of those things from progressing further. they do not define me, and they will never happen again. do those men represent every man? hell no. and i've known women who do equal level shit to men. we just don't hear about it on the nightly news.

women are powerful. accept that and stop blaming men (or the president) for taking it away from you.

text:
mijn missie is mensen te laten ervaren wat de kracht van aanraking is. in deze wereld vol #metoo verhalen en taboes lijkt aanraking het onderspit te delven, terwijl iedereen aanraking nodig heeft. ik wil mensen het vertrouwen geven dat aanraking en knuffelen bij het leven horen. heel dicht bij jezelf blijven en in elk moment goed voelen of het nog ok is, is de basis van veilig aanraken.

kijk voor meer info of een afspraak op: https://arinya.nl/massage

my mission is to let people experience the power of touch. in this world full of #metoo stories and taboos touch seems to become estranged. while everyone needs touch in their lives. i want to support people in trusting that touch and hugs belong to life. staying close to yourself and feeling in the moment if it is still ok, are the basics of touching safely.

for more information or an appointment:
https://arinya.nl/massage

text:
as i worked out this afternoon, i took a break,  and i sat down. as i sat in this park, i thought ðŸ’­ to myself how much i use to hate my childhood, but how much i loved when they took me to the park! i thought ðŸ’­ to myself, that little girl who was once sexually molested, but hid behind laughs and smiles once she was in that park! i use to hate being that little girl! but today, today, i am proud of that little girl who grew up to be a confident woman! a woman who has learned what forgiveness is, knowing that forgiveness is not for the people who hurt you but for self growth! today i am not that little girl nor i cry at my past, i thank god for it, because it made me seek my creator, who allowed me to be a better mom, wife and friend â¤ï¸ but it also taught me to help women who has been through the same thing, help them heal that little girl in their past!!!! #butgod 
#forgiveness 
#healing

text:
what happens when women speak up? great things for the most part. we are better able to communicate our value, and therefore provide value to our companies.â €
--â €
we can articulate our needs, and in so doing get the help and support we require to succeed and help our companies succeed.â €
--â €
we create open, honest and fluid relationships with our teams and bosses which increases our sense of purpose, worth and engagement all around.â €
--â €
sometimes though there are unintended consequences due in the early stages of change due to adaptation demands, like this one discussed by maya salam in the @nytgender.â €
--â €
when men perceive womenâ€™s willingness to speak up about harassment as a threat to their own safety. when they confuse the vast numbers of #metoo cases for a witch hunt, rather than a simple unveiling of the extent of this problem, they get scared.â €
--â €
companies get scared, and instead of dealing with the real issue (predatory behaviors and misconduct), they segregate, and perpetuate â€˜us v them' cultures.â €
--â €
who suffers? at first sight, women, but look closer and youâ€™ll realize everyone suffers. gender diversity and the presence of female #leadership are good not just for women but for the whole company, denying mentorship and undermining #inclusion and collaboration will not hold women back from success it will drive them away from your business.â €
--â €
we need to bridge the gap, then create better communication. we need to help women speak up, we need men to listen and teach teams to communicate.â €

text:
when i first started womb work it was almost debilitating.
.
.
i was allowing my trauma to control me and consume me, changing how i acted and responded to things because of the trauma i experienced.
.
.
it wasnt until the #metoo movement that i fully realized i'm not alone.
.
.
victim mindset does that to us. it cuts us off from our sisters and makes us feel like we're alone and we have to experience and feel everything by ourselves.
.
.
it causes shame, guilt, anxiety, depression, self loathing like whatever happened was our fault.
.
.
this is exactly why i have opened up my group womb healing sessions. .
.
i want to open a safe space for any woman who is ready to let go of those negative feelings.
.
.
i have arranged it in a group setting so it's more of a meeting of sisters and potentially less intimidating than a one on one session. .
.
we are all in this together goddess. .
.
you are safe.
.
.
you are heard.
.
.
you are unconditonally loved.
.
.
for more info comment below of dm me!
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

day update

i started school today! the culinary program is big exhausting but so fucking fun and a great learning experience. i'm really liking it so far. still worried about being there every single day though :/ but i'm really going to try

home time now. social anxiety makes the bus a real bad time but with the killers blasting through my headphones it's more bearable. howre y'all?

for months after my assault, i was extremely jealous of sex trafficking survivors. because as survivors, they have more support than rape survivors have by not just millimeters, but by yards.  they have access to housing and resources that, we as rape survivors do not qualify for. they also, as survivors, are removed from the surroundings in which they were caused harm. as rape survivors, we often have no means of getting away from our assaulter or leaving the area that we were assaulted at. they are rescued, and rape survivors are often left to rescue themselves. all of these things left me bitter and even more broken to realise that being raped wasn't enough to have access to the same needed care. that i would have to be sold and raped.
ðŸ’Ž
however, over the past couple of years, god has been slowly softening my heart and changing the bitterness into belief that education can bridge the gap between the resources that sex trafficking survivors have access to and the resources that rape survivors have access too.  and the brokenness is being built into a fire, a flame actually, to advocate for rape survivors to be just as fought for and provided for as trafficking survivors.
ðŸ’Ž
god has brought me to this point of realisation that it is not one fight against another, but a fight that needs to be fought together. so the question now is: how do we make that happen? #hannahrosela #noimperfectionsorg

text: a most powerful and inspiring conversation with 2018 nobel peace prize laureate dr. denis mukwege and eve ensler. dr. mukwege is the worldâ€™s leading specialist in the treatment of wartime sexual violence and a global campaigner against the use of rape as a weapon of war. he reiterated last night that rape and violence against women is not just a womenâ€™s issue. we need men to stand with women against the violence that is being perpetrated. women cannot do it alone. it really is a menâ€™s issue.  if you donâ€™t know dr. mukwege or eve ensler please check out what they have accomplished with city of joy a revolutionary center for women survivors of violence in the democratic republic of congo. watch the documentary city of joy on #netflix for many this may be an eye opener. we cannot remain ignorant of the fact that we are partly to blame for what is happening there and in other places around the world.  the people in this #documentary show remarkable strength and courage. @eveensler #congo #violenceagainstwomen #metoo #domesticviolence #courage #strength #nobelpeacelaureate @drdenismukwege #peace #justice #huntercollege @huntercollege #hero

text:
i felt this on so many different levels. if i could force feed my younger self and some of today's generation this message, my outlook on life would be through completely different lens. we all live together on the same planet yes, but we travel different journeys. our limits, boundaries, and drive are all different. it would be foolish to measure yourself using someone else's measuring stick. stay in your lane and focus on the tools needed for your destination. when the destination is different, the resources needed to get there are different. be the best version of yourself. not the best to complete a flawed and robotic idea that everyone is trying to fit into. get to know yourself. what makes you, you. and once you find those things, making your mark on the world will come naturally ðŸ’– i love you guys xoxo
.
do i ever make any sense to you all when you read my writings? do you get anything out of them or this post? feedback is highly important to me! .
.
.

.
do i ever make any sense to you all when you read my writings? do you get anything out of them or this post? feedback is highly important to me! .
.
.

text:
*tw* two years ago, today. seven months before #metoo and exactly one lifetime ago. i'm not the same person who stood on that ted stage, about to bare her deepest wounds to 5 million viewers. and yet there's not a single word in the talk i wouldn't say again. for my fellow survivors who shouldered blame that was never theirs to carry. for those struggling with shame that never belonged to them. for the lost teenager i once was. for those who are still suffering in solitude. for my brave sisters around the world who are speaking up. but mostly for the children of the future, who will live free from the silence we broke. this is for you. ðŸ”¥ðŸ”¥ðŸ”¥
(link to the full-length talk in bio)
#survivor #stoprapeculture #notmyskirt #notmysmile #stopslutshaming #fuckshame #bethechange #tedtalks #southofforgiveness #healing #untiltheviolencestops

text:
with the grammys coming up, following the last year's controversy with the recording academy president saying thatÂ women have to â€œstep up,â€Â how do you hope the awards show better embraces women this year?

ldr:Â i forgot he said that; that was unexpected. i guess to begin with, alicia keys is hosting. so there's that, basic 101, female host. but as a whole, i think we're moving in the right direction by having the conversation about some of the perils of being a female in the workplace. i'm very grateful that it hasn't just gone away because that's what i thought was going to happen, that the whole issue was going to be raised that there are problems, and then people would be like, "yeah we know," and then it would just sort of disappear. but it seems like there was a resounding response to the #metoo movement and to some of these issues that have been brought up by people in movies and music that really resonated with a lot of women. i think the good thing about it was a lot of the good men in many fields have gotten to share these stories that they never knew about because a lot of women were too embarrassed to share them.
so now you've got a lot of players on the tune, you've got a lot of the good guys stepping in trying to give a voice to even more women who maybe haven't had a voice in the past, and i'm really grateful for that. i do feel like we're moving in the right direction, and i think the music business knows the value of its female singers. we can only go forward from here at this point, because i music is getting better and better. in the last five years, there's been so many alternative voices coming through; not just pop music, but people sharing their stories through words, a little reminiscent of some of those old '60s and '70s records ." lana for harper'sbazaar -

text:
this project was stemmed from a conversation i had about the â€œme tooâ€ movement,
the opinions expressed to me sparked a feminist rage inside, and all of a sudden, an idea was born.
i wonâ€™t get into the details, instead iâ€™ll explain the positive aspect that came from it- the red lip district.
i want a place where women feel comfortable and safe opening up about their experiences with sexual harassment.
a place where they can speak up and start taking back their power.
a place where they are never questioned, only supported by others for sharing their stories.

i decided to call it â€œthe red lip districtâ€ as a play off of the red light district, a place where the women working are seen negatively, and the words used to describe them have also been used towards the survivors of sexual harassment, violence and assault. 
i want to break the stigma. i want women to take back their power.

text:
new york (cnn) - the new york state legislature passed a bill that will increase the statute of limitations for cases of child sexual abuse.

the child victims act will allow child victims to seek prosecution against their abuser until the age of 55 in civil cases, a significant increase from the previous limit of age 23. for criminal cases, victims can seek prosecution until they turn 28. the bill also includes a one-year window during which victims of any age or time limit can come forward to prosecute. "new york has just gone from being one of the worst states in the country to being one of the best," in terms of the statute of limitations for child sex abuse cases, said marci hamilton, ceo of child usa and a professor at the university of pennsylvania.

hamilton said the bill "represents over 15 years of work by survivors and advocates trying to get around the stiff opposition from the catholic bishops and the insurance industry" and is a step forward in the national conversation. there are eight other states considering similar legislation.

full story: https://www-m.cnn.com/2019/01/28/us/new-york-child-victims-act/index.html

text:
this photo is from the first #metoo production i did. this was nothing short of life changing. it didnâ€™t seem like it at the time, but looking back, this is when i truly realized the value of my story and my voice. how it helps and heals. i also couldnâ€™t of started this journey with a stronger group of people. i look forward to being in my third production of the #metoo monologues. iâ€™m telling a different story this time, i just needed some time to heal from the past year and losing my mother before i continue to share that story. for those of you that do know she was the last person i called when i was kidnapped, i thought i was going to die so i wanted to leave her a voicemail telling her i loved her. so with losing her last may, i just need a little time. however i look forward to sharing my new story in april.
.

.

text_retweet:
reposted from @belinda_vegan - â—½â—½â—½â—½â—½swipe ðŸ‘ˆ 
please read ðŸ‘‰downed cow: the true story of one anonymous animal born into the meat industry
the truck carrying this cow was unloaded one september morning. after the other animals were removed from the truck, she was left behind, unable to move. the stockyard workers used their customary electric prods in her ear to try to get her to move, then beat and kicked her in the face, ribs, and back but still she couldn't move. they tied a rope around her neck, tied the other end to a post in the ground and drove the truck away. the cow was dragged along the floor of the truck and fell to the ground, landing with both hind legs and her pelvis broken. she remained like that until 7:30 that evening.
_
for the first three hours, she lay in the hot sun crying out. periodically, when she urinated or defecated, she used her front legs to drag herself along the gravel to a clean spot. she also tried to crawl to a shaded area but couldn't move far enough. altogether, she managed to crawl a painful 13 to 14 yards. the stockyard employees wouldn't allow her any drinking water.
_
at 4:30 p.m. three dogs were attacking the cow who was still alive. she had suffered a number of bite wounds. the stockyard workers would not euthanize her, claiming that in order to preserve the value of meat, she could not be destroyed. the butcher eventually arrived at 7:30 p.m. and shot her. her body was purchased for $307.50
_
now you know. the question is what will you do? every bite of animal products that you take involves fear, cruelty, immense suffering, pain and death. ask yourself when you can not only survive but thrive on a plant-based diet, why wouldn't you? âž¡ï¸www.vegankit.com

cw fatphobia, rape, sexual assault (graphic description of injuries). i feel like this isnâ€™t spoken about enough. when iâ€™ve told people about the time i was raped and the times i was sexually assaulted, people didnâ€™t believe me. iâ€™ve been told i was making it up. iâ€™ve been told i was over exaggerating. 
think about the way rape culture is used against fat people for a second. have you ever been told that that fat people are â€˜more gratefulâ€™ for sex? that fat people are â€˜better at giving headâ€™? has someone ever tried to have sex with you and when you denied their advances they say â€˜whatever youâ€™re fat anywayâ€™? this is how society dehumanises fat people. make us into â€˜easy targetsâ€™. make us into objects they can use and throw away, cause they know less people will care. 
weâ€™re either treated as disgusting, or weâ€™re fetishised to a point where weâ€™re not even seen as people. 
iâ€™m not going to go into detail about the rape and the assaults iâ€™ve faced, but one of the cases involved a man who fetishised my body so much, that he essentially beat me, thinking i wouldnâ€™t feel it, and left me with bruises all over my breasts. even when i was telling him to stop. he just kept saying â€˜i love your big bodyâ€™. i wasnâ€™t a person to him in that moment. i was an object to abuse. 
does this happen to slim people too? yes. 
but are fat survivors of abuse less likely to be believed because of what they look like? hell yes. 
whenever iâ€™ve told people iâ€™ve been assaulted multiple times, they look taken aback. it takes me telling them details to believe me. 
when i confronted the man who raped me, he acted as if i consented. he acted like what he did to me wasnâ€™t â€˜real rapeâ€™. he undermined me and told me i was wrong. 
believe fat survivors of sexual assault. 
include fat survivors in your activism. we deserve to tell our stories and be believed too. 
if youâ€™re comfortable, please share your experiences with being treated like an object due to your size, and not being believed, below. .

text:
nbc's tom brokaw, 78, has been accused of sexual misconduct by two women.
- former nbc correspondent, linda vester, claimed he made unwanted advances
- the alleged incidents occurred in the 1990s and included one forcible kiss
- another woman, who worked as a production assistant in the 1990s when she was 24, claims that brokaw put her 'hands under his jacket and against his chest'
- he then allegedly asked the woman to go back to his office after his show #metoo #nbc

text:
10 things you might wanna stop believing 
1. love has boundaries. it doesn't. people make it that way but the facts are people from different religions/tribes/faiths have fallen in love and will continue to do so

2. it takes money to affect change. false. it takes heart, a plan, dedication, a loyal following, and a big middle finger to the establishment...all of these are free

3. business is never personal. companies and ceo's have taken great pride in demolishing their competition. you think steve jobs didn't light up a cigar when the zune failed? you think phil knight doesn't laugh a lil bit when other companies launch a new shoe knowing he can release a shoe made in 94 and it still sell? business is very personal laterally. you know when its not? between superiors and subordinates.  suddenly downsizing is 'not personal'

4. kids are cruel. no, we breed that as a society and allow it

5. boys wiil be boys. #metoo #timesup #endfukbois kinda kills that

6. you need to dress for your size. nah. dress how you like and if someone doesn't like it, you have a middle finger right?

7. it's alway gonna be like this/things will never change. with that mindset, it wont.

8. we just need to vote in the right people *facepalm* ok.... 9. just do squats to build a big booty
*facepalm again* ok

10. most people don't care/are bad
might wanna figure out where you got that narrative... #10things #10thingsthursday #thinkaboutit #foodforthought #dontbelivethehype #politics #boyswillbeboys #metoo #timesup #squats #voteordie #love #money #getrichordietrying

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

the guardian

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
so as you may know i run this account for my mom and her and i have decided  to share my story. this year a boy from my high school sexually assulated me by groping my butt. i asked him to stop and he continued to pursue. i told the administrators at my school. they had me  tell them what he did. after i told them they said they would handle it but couldn't  tell me how  they handle it. i was supposed to be moved out of the class with  this boy, but my counselor said she couldn't  move me and so i spent the whole semester  in the same class with that boy. he never came up to me again... or at least in person. his friends harassed me for him. and i told my mom  who brought to the administrators  who said they would handle it. they didn't  handle. so my  mom and i decided  i was done  with highschool, because i was already  an outstanding student who finished  my work early in each class and felt bored and because  of this predicament.  so i tried to withdrawl from school and they told me nevause of my age i could not withdrawl. i needed  to withdrawl so i could get my ged because i am also underaged for that as well. but in order to get the age waiver i needed  to be withdrawn  from my school. amd since that can not happen  i am stuck. i can go to the college but i would have to pay the tuition  until im 17(the legal age for me to get my ged). i  feel like all these laws put in place have caught me in a web that i am not unable to escape. i am almost an adult yet the laws that are put in place to " protect" me are only  holding me back.
#unfairsystem
#metoo

- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

.

text:
how many of you have heard about sara?  itâ€™s not one of the most commonly talked about oils, but it sure is one incredible oil.  hereâ€™s why:

sara is a powerful blend of oils that is excellent for emotional release.  the acronym sara stands for sexual and ritual abuse as it was created for those who battle with emotions from this kind of trauma as well as other forms of physical and emotional abuse.  itâ€™s not limited to those who have suffered abuse, however.  each one of us could find a purpose for using sara.  any sort of negative emotions we have stored deep down inside would warrant needing this oil.

follow with me for a minute:

emotions that we bury deep down inside of us never actually die.  we canâ€™t just stuff them down and expect them to go away with time. quite the contrary, in fact!  our negative emotions from difficult situations that we have endured in our life are written on our dna and stored in the cellular memory within our organs and in our amygdala (our brainâ€™s memory center for fear and trauma). each time a thought or situation causes us to bring up these old thoughts and emotions, we reinforce it in our cellular memory, allowing it to grow and wreak havoc on our emotional well-being as well as our physical bodyâ€¦eventually causing physical ailments (because, remember, itâ€™s written on the cells in our organs). we must release these emotions rather than stuffing them down if we want to achieve optimal health and wellness.

did your parents make you feel ashamed of yourself? reach for sara and release it.  did your husband make you feel unloved or abandoned? reach for sara and release it.  did a friend make you feel unworthy or lonely? reach for sara and release it.  do you have unresolved negative emotions that you thought you buried alive but now realize you need to dig up and release?  reach for sara.  youâ€™ll be thankful you have this special oil on hand, i promise.

today we honor tarana burke ( @taranajaneen )- black civil rights activist and founder of the #metoo movement. in 2017 burke was named time person of the year and dubbed one of "the silence breakers" for her work raising awareness of the pervasiveness of sexual abuse and assault in society. burke continues her activism and passion for helping young women through empowering speaking engagements, program development and policy improvement. join us in honoring our sister warrior, tarana burke!

text:
image3- india's first transgender lawyer: sathyasri sharmila (36). shunning the stereotypical mindset behind, she set an example by pursuing law so that she can fight against the injustice.
. 
image4-india's first transgender judge: joyita mondal(29).she was appointed at lok adalat in north bengal in october 2017. while closely working for transgender rights organisations, mondal got inspired to pursue a degree in law.
. 
image5- india's first transgender police officer: prithika yashini. though she was declared failed by one mark. nonetheless, she got her score re-evaluated in the physical examination and came out clear with flying colours.
. 
image6 - india's first transgender college principal: manabi bandopadhyay. currently, she is the professor and also became the first transgender person in india who has completed doctor of philosophy (phd).
. 
image7 - india's first transgender person to contest elections: mumtaz. a social worker, is the first transgender who came out to contest elections in punjab from bahujan samaj party (bsp). . 
image8- india's first transgender who became an mla: shabnam mausi. 
she contested elections from sohagpur constituency in district shahdol, madhya pradesh. as she was not supported by her family, she wasn't able to attend school, yet she learnt almost 12 different languages.
. 
image9- india's first transgender soldier: shabi. she joined marine engineering department of the eastern naval command around eight years ago. however, she underwent the sex reassignment surgery in 2016 in delhi. after the surgery she joined the naval base in vishakhapatnam.
. 
10-india's first transgender medical assistant: jiya das. she became the first transgender operation theatre or ot technician.
source: @indiatoday
________________________________

text:
thrilled and proud to announce that my mom nancy bacon's memoir legends and lipstick is all spiffed up for 2019 with a brand new and topical foreword by excellent author stacey keith, additional revisions, and a heartfelt epilogue by yours truly. it's now #26 in the kindle store under memoirs! i still miss my mom every day, and so i am very pleased to be able to help facilitate her legacy.  legends and lipstick tells tales of #hollywood -- there's glitz, glamour and fun, but also heartbreak and a hard look back at #metoo long before the era of outrage and hashtags. it's available via #kindle, #paperback, and #audiobook .
.
.
from the foreword by stacey keith: "society isnâ€™t kind to women who enjoy sex, unless they have the decency to die young. marilyn monroe and jayne mansfield are objects of the kind of cult worship that happens when you are preserved forever in the popular imagination. nancy knew them both. hollywoodâ€”more specifically, men in hollywoodâ€”used up all three women. marilyn died of a drug overdose, jayne in a gruesome car crash, and nancy very nearly of alcoholism, but the dynamics were the same." #marilynmonroe #jaynemansfield #oldhollywood #feminism #books

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text: i just reported the sexual abuses and rape i endured as a six year old to the police. this goes against all my instincts and codes of the street. some of my friends might be disappointed about this. we don't go to the police for any reason. but i do what god directs me too. god told me to give up my desires for vengence. that this hate will destroy me and my life, and therefore destroy the divine mission i have been given. to save our street kids(children and youth). god told me to report this to the police. i need to lead by example. if you have been sexually abused you need to report it. we are not responsible for what happened as kids, but we are responsible in how we handle it. we need to be brave and face our fears. otherwise this vicious cycle continues. you see pedophiles don't change, these two men will still be committing acts of abuse and rape. this is no time to hesitate. there needs to be a record, so that it alerts the police and the crown (attorney general) that these evil men are in their communities. i have been haunted my whole life by what happened as a child. i've had overwhelmingly feelings of self hate, guilt and shame. i've had thoughts of suicide my whole life. i've almost killed myself countless times. well no more. i am taking a stand against these most vile, wretched and evil of men. yes i think they deserve to die and yes i hope they burn in hell. but god says in the bible "vengence is mine saith the lord". by having desires of vengence and retribution, to kill them, darkness and anger clouds my heart and soul. as my family and friends know my rage is all consuming. i can not keep living with anger and rage in my heart. it will destroy me. god told me by giving up these desires for vengence, i can start to actually heal. i need to let love back in my heart. it is essential for my life and my mission to save these precious children. i can not display my anger around them. they will be too fragile. this will scare them and they will not feel safe. if i am to help these kids. they must feel safe, secure and most of all, they must feel loved. then they will be able to trust and to heal. for love conquers all â¤ï¸ #metoo #moveforward #heal

text:
day 7 of sexual abuse in the black community: "in 1997, tarana burke sat across from a 13-year-old girl who was disclosing her experience of sexual abuse. overwhelmed by the feeling, (burke herself first experienced sexual abuse at age 6 according to reports) she resolved to become a source of support for fellow survivors. in 2006, tarana burke founded the #metoo movement to help survivors of sexual violence, particularly young women of color from low-income communities, find pathways to healing. #metoo went viral last october when celebrities (notably alyssa milano) began using the hashtag, but burke has been doing this work for years." https://www.safehorizon.org/programs/4-black-survivors-advocates-sexual-assault/

text:
don't let the past swallow your future

many persons, are still struggling with their identity because they had lost their true identity due to abuse. to anyone who was sexually abused and still traumatized by the hurt, i assure you that there is hope. 
do not give in to depression or even suicide. you must refuse to allow the devil win by being trapped in those painful memories. 
your pain can be your gain. yes, it was terrible because you were ripped apart by that act but 
you can find peace from those dreadful flashbacks, depression, guilt, shame, low self-esteem, bitterness, suicidal tendencies, trouble sleeping etc. 
there is healing in god's arms. you can be truly whole. you can find freedom again and that i assure you  from my heart.  make the decision not to let your past keep you from your future. 
#nomorehiding

#zerotoleranceforabuse

#metoo

#hearmetoo

#unwomen

text:
first essay in our #metoo series. 
how photographer mahesh shantaram got away with #metooâ  â  â€œshantaram begins his facebook post by vehemently declaring his liberal, feminist credentials. even shantaramâ€™s instagram page carries the slogan â€œfuck patriarchy,â€ although it isnâ€™t quite clear how he intends or proposes to do that given that his career is largely based on the photographing of that most patriarchal of social institutions, the heterosexual marriage. he insists that he has â€œbeen a vocal upholder of feminist causes and a fighter of the good fightâ€ but no evidence of this claim is offered or available for us to see. he goes on to argue, â€œi know that no means no, and i know to take no for an answer,â€ echoing the now popular â€œno means noâ€ slogan associated with anti-rape movements.

so why does he begin here? he wants the reader to know that he is a man who is incapable of doing what the women have accused him of doing. these assertions of feminist warrior-hood and of knowing when no means no assume that those who fight the feminist fight cannot be sexual harassers or those who stand with feminists cannot be abusers or those who â€œfight the good fightâ€ cannot be predators.â€ by @suchitravijayan . read&share! @project_polis, @indiametoo, #art, #photography, #india, #timesup
https://www.thepolisproject.com/how-an-artist-gets-away-with-metoo-autopsy-of-an-apology/

text:
"that is every boy's fantasy"...
the conversation around child sexual abuse can often focus on female victims and survivors, but males are being sexually abused at alarming rates as well. however, they are even far less likely to disclose sexual abuse than females. one reason is male victims who are sexually abused by females are often made to feel as though they should be happy about having a sexual encounter because that is "what every male wants". but, that is a lie! anytime an adult female (or a significantly older female minor) engages in any sexual contact with a boy or a young man, that is sexual abuse/assault, and boys and young men do not want to be sexually abused/assaulted. it is not a badge of honor for them, it is indeed a violation. and, while their bodies may be naturally stimulated, it is still very mentally and emotionally traumatic. just like females, they carry the burden of the violation and without professional counseling, they too can experience lifelong effects that manifest themselves in a myriad of ways. the idea that boys simply want to be engaged sexually and by any female (even one who is attractive) is simply not true. they don't desire to have control of their bodies stripped from them anymore than a female does. so, if you're a boy or young man who has been sexually abused, stand in your truth. we stand with you! we know you didn't want to be violated. and, we most certainly know it wasn't your fantasy. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #super bowl

a strong woman isnâ€™t for murdering her children or countless others.

text:
the redemption of the wounded masculine 
for all the times i was told to get over it
to be strong 
to hold back my tears and power through my grief 
to get over my trauma 
i rage now, an unkept ferocious energy runs through my veins destroying everything in its wake 
finding its repressed roots in the conscious world

it burns my world down 
in my lust for power
in my desperate seeking of validation for my existence 
in my enslavement to money and fame 
in my hatred of the feminine 
in my objectified  and brutally punishing sexuality 
in my addictions to pleasure 
in my emotionally vacant heart

more and more it screams 
fill the hollowness 
mask my pain
hide my shame 
in the ashes of the aftermath of toxic masculinity 
i lay bound in the tyranny of the chains of my unconscious slavery 
the land is parched 
my breath is shallow
a soft and broken voice inside me cries for mercy

and then a drop of water falls from the heaven 
touches my cheek 
and as it does my being is overwhelmed with compassion 
tears begin to flow freely 
the grief, the trauma, the broken parts all ascend into the light of the divine masculine 
i am redeemed 
i am held in a compassion that only wishes to take away my suffering
i surrender 
i am carried higher by my divine father 
my heart is ready to meet my mother 
upward 
i rise
and dissolve into her light

i am free at last
nothing to become
nowhere to go

all is as is 
complete 
there is peace 
i dissolve into the light - davita moodley

please feel free to follow this page, friend request and share this poem and message, so it may bring healing and love. may we all allow this healing to take place within us. 
the war is not between men and women. it is within our own hearts and minds. may we each meet and heal our wounded masculinity and femininity. #healing #metoo #healing

â—½â—½â—½â—½â—½swipe ðŸ‘ˆ 
please read ðŸ‘‰downed cow: the true story of one anonymous animal born into the meat industry
the truck carrying this cow was unloaded one september morning. after the other animals were removed from the truck, she was left behind, unable to move. the stockyard workers used their customary electric prods in her ear to try to get her to move, then beat and kicked her in the face, ribs, and back but still she couldn't move. they tied a rope around her neck, tied the other end to a post in the ground and drove the truck away. the cow was dragged along the floor of the truck and fell to the ground, landing with both hind legs and her pelvis broken. she remained like that until 7:30 that evening.
_
for the first three hours, she lay in the hot sun crying out. periodically, when she urinated or defecated, she used her front legs to drag herself along the gravel to a clean spot. she also tried to crawl to a shaded area but couldn't move far enough. altogether, she managed to crawl a painful 13 to 14 yards. the stockyard employees wouldn't allow her any drinking water.
_
at 4:30 p.m. three dogs were attacking the cow who was still alive. she had suffered a number of bite wounds. the stockyard workers would not euthanize her, claiming that in order to preserve the value of meat, she could not be destroyed. the butcher eventually arrived at 7:30 p.m. and shot her. her body was purchased for $307.50
_
now you know. the question is what will you do? every bite of animal products that you take involves fear, cruelty, immense suffering, pain and death. ask yourself when you can not only survive but thrive on a plant-based diet, why wouldn't you? âž¡ï¸www.vegankit.com

text:
there is a healing power in creative expression. 
yesterday i had a papsmeer. when you've had a very crappy childhood sexual abuse experience certain things are painful triggers.. this was definitely one of them.
our bodies store memories physically, muscle memory. the flood of memories and bodily sensations can be as traumatic as the original incident. they threaten to overwhelm and capsize you with the intensity of each wave/flood of memory.

i always yearn to cut it out, cut myself open and just pour out the painful sensations so they cannot take up space in my skin my body my heart my soul and their permanent residence;my mind!

art has become this escape, i'll mindlessly or frantically pick up my materials and put every unnamed, unprocessed, unsure emotion onto paper. i cannot always verbalise the feelings. but the paper willingly takes them, holds them and transforms them from murky, dark, fearbased anxiety into a form i can recognise.

i was too young and vulnerable to understand what was happening, my adult self breaks to pieces with each intrusive memory, desperate to shield my child self from the horrors no child should even know exists.

complex post traumatic shock syndrome (no longer classed as a disorder but a symptom of trauma) is manageable. it is brutal. it can feel overwhelming beyond measure but your mind can heal from those brutal wounds. we might limp slightly but broken bones heal stronger and broken souls heal fiercer!
#metoo #nfiniteheart #mentalhealth #cptsd #cptssrecovery #ptsd #ptss #trauma #mentalillness #chronicillness #healing #art #arttherapy #creative #musclememory #selfcare #community #survivor #triggers
